On Wednesday MHD Prague will accompany you for the first time also with an electronic card
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date on which the first passengers who will have an electronic card in their pocket instead of the paper ticket will get on the metro, tram and bus.
At the moment they can get around 100,000 people who own their own Opencard card.
Passengers can buy the 30 and 90-day and annual one (which will be valid from January 1, 2009) and at the same time be charged their card in the Infopoints and offices of the Transport Company and at the metro station Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra ? Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
You can buy coupons from yesterday on the Internet at the page of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred customers took advantage of the service before the afternoon.
Those who start using the internet service can completely forget the counters in the subway stops where they had to make long lines for paper tickets so far.
The coupon is bought over the internet and on the Opencard they charge it on one of the twelve branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places passengers have at their disposal a desk with trained staff that will help those interested in the purchase on the internet and will also record on their card the credit acquired." said the spokesman for the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons on the Opencards to ATMs and self-service which are installed at the entrances of the metro.
How are these ATMs?
They are red, they resemble ticket obliterators and passengers have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stops.
"Now there are five in the whole city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," concluded Opatrný.
The coupon will be checked instead of by the driver from the ATM.
The ATM service that will work tomorrow is very simple.
Simply enter the Opencard card and after payment of the coupon, it will charge on top.
The electronic cards are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, in the urban lines of trains and buses from the number 300 to 499, which the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia take to reach the capital.
"In added trains in Prague's integrated transport there are controllers equipped with card readers with whom they verify the temporal and zonal validity," explained the mode of checking Filip tickets by the Ropid organization, which develops the timetables for collective transport in Prague.
Urban buses have card readers integrated into the driver’s case.
During the ascent it is necessary not only to show the magnetic card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard at the fixed point next to the cash register.
So the driver checks the validity of the coupons loaded.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the coupons loaded, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this kind of information," Drápal added.
Passengers who take urban buses and do not remember, when the coupon expires, can go back to the self-service ATMs, where the coupons are loaded on the card.
Here you will see information on the validity of their documents on the screen of the apparatus.
The Sudetian Germans wanted a referendum from the USA
The Sudetian Germans in 1945 asked to include Šumava in the United States.
This is the result of the letter deposited in the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States.
With this desire, according to what is said, some groups of Germans of the Sudetians turned in 1945 to the President of the United States.
This is more than anything else from the letter kept in a private archive and now deposited in the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask in the letter to the American President not to allow the return of the "Sumava district" – occupied by Hitler under the Munich agreement – to Czechoslovakia.
