Hidden in the theme park extended on the suburbs of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the enormous, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American experience enter life.
Eatonville, the first black town incorporated in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, Harlem Renaissance's most famous writer.
Yet in many ways, the city that he described - and that makes tourists stop by understanding it in the Florida tourist guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project - remains a separate place.
It is so independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that "knowing so little about us, he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very cautious about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It has to be fair."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black gripping and a community of almost 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shade of the oaks of the rural culture of the blacks of the south - sometimes disdained, sometimes rewarded - born from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's imagination really began with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere books, rich in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off the Rout 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida within a scenario from black history and human drama
Low as a drum in both life and literature, Hurston brought readers to the store owned by the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then diverted them to more private areas.
"Outside the street on the left," he wrote, "it's the modern public school, brown with its white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of the widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever suits the passage rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora used to say it like it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls who Hurston captures by quoting men singing gross songs about their beauty.
He adds, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from his family moving to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston came into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today boasts of decent clothing.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others were smirking.
"People were always very happy to see Zora," said Mr. Franklin.
But, he added, swinging in his chair on the patio on the back overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed for long".
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary from Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a grave without a plaque in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no great memorial ceremonies, and no great conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officers wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in his history.
Forced integration, in addition to other things, had brought an end to its idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's home door.
