Talking in your sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not talking about those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but about those children who speak while they are asleep.
The first time that happens, at most you get a scare, but it really doesn't matter much.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquy.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (wetting in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it may be associated with very high fever stages, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is still a phenomenon that has not been studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, when coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, on the other hand, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid TV shows or shows that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more comfortably.
Once the somniloquies appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day they will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
