Sarkozy meets fishermen in anger
Before leaving for the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a stop in Brittany.
In view of the demonstration of the fishermen who on Monday brutally prevented access to several Breton and Norman ports, the President of the Republic decided to go Tuesday morning to the port of Guilvinec, in the department of Finistère, to enchant its representatives.
The latter have promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that "he will present himself with concrete proposals".
A presidential visit that takes place at the same time as the general assembly of the "crisis committee", created by the fishermen of Brittany in order to adopt measures to cope with the surge in the price of diesel oil, which has reached its record with an average of more than 1,14 euros per litre.
According to Elysée David Martinon's spokesman, the president "will discuss with them possible solutions to help businesses regain competitiveness and to secure working conditions and the remuneration of sailors".
The fishermen wait for Nicolas Sarkozy to stand still.
On Tuesday morning, they conducted "snail operations" in Morbihan and Calvados, causing almost 10 km of traffic jams.
Also the port of Quiberon was blocked, but the connections with Belle-île were not interrupted.
On the Quiberon Peninsula a roadblock has been implemented.
On Monday the sailors have already demonstrated their determination by burning, starting from dawn, tires and pallets in front of the fuel depots at the ports of Brest and Lorient, while demonstrations took place in Concarneau and Saint-Brieuc.
The movement extended to the ports of the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, such as Sables d'Olonne, in Vendée, where the vessels remained at the pier, or to Havre, where about twenty boats prevented the movement of commercial ships.
The fishermen of La Turballe et del Croisic, near the Loire Atlantica, interrupted in the evening the blockade of the famous Total refinery of Donges.
In Boulogne-sur-Mer they decided to wait for the meeting to be held on Wednesday at the Ministry to decide on possible actions.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" will decide on Tuesday the future actions of the movement and the possible participation in the meeting scheduled for the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by those in charge of the National Fisheries Committee, who did not support the movement.
"The strike will continue" because "fishers will not give up" and "they will not move to Paris", announced, for example, Liliane Cariou, president of the Lorient Fisheries Committee.
Professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel fuel, currently pay about 50 cents per litre, but estimate that the efficiency limit of a boat is reached only with a diesel less than 0,30 euros per litre.
