The New York Stock Exchange suffered a historic collapse on Monday, after the House of Representatives voted against the Paulson plan to rescue financial institutions: the Dow Jones lost 6,98%, a decrease never seen, approaching 800 points, and the Nasdaq 9.14%.
The Dow Jones Industrial Media (DJIA) finished at 10,365.45, down 777.68 points.
In terms of points, the worst loss in its history (684,81 points) higher than that of 17 September 2001, the day of the reopening of the Stock Exchanges following the terrorist attacks of 11 September.
The Nasdaq, the index of the main technological titles, lost 199.61 points closing to 1.983.73 and the expanded index Standard & Poor's 500 lost 8.81% (i.e. 106.85 points) closing to 1,106.55, according to the final closing figures.
Demoralized at the beginning of the session, Wall Street sank after the unexpected rejection of the bank bailout plan, designed to restore stability to the markets.
By 228 votes against the plan and 205 in favour, the representatives rejected the funding requested by Treasury Minister Trésor Henry Paulson.
About two out of three Republicans rejected the plan.
"It's a negative signal sent to the market, which sees Congress unable to adopt a plan," said Lindsey Piegza, of FTN Financial.
"All this indicates how much the market was counting on the project," he added, fearing that in a few days it might already be "too late" to adopt one.
"If the project were actually dying (...) then the witness would quickly be transferred to the Fed – Federal Reserve – (the US central bank, ed.) and to the other central banks to resolve the crisis, which would further limit credit conditions," said Brian Bethune, head of finance and economy at Global Insight.
And again highlighting its state of emergency, "every day that passes leads to the collapse of a financial institution" in the United States, stressed the Piegza.
After the failure of Washington Mutual on Friday, the authorities organized the purchase of the banking activities of Wachovia by rival Citygroup.
In Europe, the crisis has accelerated sharply, calling for urgent intervention in favour of banks in the United Kingdom, Benelux, Iceland and Germany, a sign that markets "are not only facing an American crisis, but a global crisis", added the analyst at FTN Financial.
The bond market has risen strongly.
The return on Treasury bonds with a maturity of 10 years has fallen to 3.632%, compared to 3.827% on Friday evening, while the one with a maturity of 30 years is 4.161%, compared to 4.357% on the previous day.
