The meeting - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, since Héma-Québec has become one of the most secure and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee to devise a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Québec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the system of donations in Québec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec had now confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the one who has been the president since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we absolutely did not know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports was therefore that when doubts arise and a serious illness may arise, in this case, the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself in a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, is being excluded.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for a few years now, it has been shown that this disease is no doubt transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has thus shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow the presence of the virus in donors' blood to be recognized directly and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which instead the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed the window period to be reduced, i.e. from the moment the person has contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and of not being able to detect them has thus decreased considerably.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will have to be distributed before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples every year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmitted by a transfusion to be found.
I believe that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of Héma-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As cancer treatment is more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average accounts for only 3% of Québec's inhabitants who are acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who are 18 years old and meet eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where it is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Shortcomings are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they grow old and can no longer make donations.
Now it's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and incite them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frenetic that it's hardly an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eye globes and skin heart valves that are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Héma-Québec, which operates the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds in blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion in the bank of our thousandth sample of cordon blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of cordon blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
