Charest points to the North
The Prime Minister does not exclude the start of the elections before the end of the year.
After concluding the General Council of the Liberal Party, Jean Charest went yesterday to Jean-Talon, Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc, (left) tried to be elected during today's partial elections.
"Enlarge the borders of our last great north frontier": this is Jean Charest's long-term ambition, presented yesterday in Levis, by means of instruments with a strong visual impact, on the occasion of the General Council of the Liberal Party of Quebec.
Behind him, during his speech, the projection of a sort of "image mill".
On three large screens, they were confused with the spectacular negatives of hydroelectric dams, mining, images of Quebec seen with "Google Maps", maps, etc.
Large means as in the campaign.
During the press conference, moreover, the Prime Minister refused to exclude the start of the autumn elections, although he pointed out that he was very busy.
The "North Plan" is the fourth point of a "project" that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic area", which includes a first agreement with France on labour, a second agreement between Canada and Europe and other agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the most recent speeches of the Prime Minister, the opening of the North - the northern territory to the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
However, the Prime Minister simply explained why the North would be "a jewel with immense potential", but he did not say anything about timing or investment quotas, as he did not explain what the precise priorities will be in the implementation of future projects.
At most, it was limited to pointing out what it considered to be a priority position: hydroelectricity, forests, but above all the mining sector, which has experienced several improvements following the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
According to the list drawn up by Charest, the North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titan, and even diamonds".
That "land twice the size of France", it's here, it's Quebec.
Not only is it here, but it is inherent in us," he insisted, as if he wanted to urge a national founding myth.
The foundations of Quebec are rooted in his relationship with the North, he stressed: gold fever in Abitibis, national engineering, James Bay.
"It's up to us, it's our future," he added, after a theatrical pause to contemplate the immense map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a part of the Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the Prime Minister said during the press conference.
"It is a position traditionally maintained by all governments.
There is a border line on which no agreement has been in place for a long time, and when the opportunity arises, I will reiterate that position in the name of the government," he said.
Moreover," considering climate change, it is necessary to re-evaluate the North", he said talking about the north-west passage, which will be open throughout the year due to the melting of the ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister estimates that occupying the territory is a duty."
And the locals, the First Nations and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very careful about this and that the project would meet their interests, especially those of young people.
Two former ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former MEP of the Hungarian FP), have already started consulting some thirty communities.
An interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) holds an important position, started work.
The Prime Minister does not exclude a great meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment when "common visions will be provided"
The development of the North would follow the principles of sustainable development.
The North Plan will be "concerted, ordered and will respect the environment", he promised.
Jean Charest described this "project" as a continuum with that of the liberal prime ministers who preceded it.
"Like the liberals who preceded us, we know how to stand out to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development."
This was also one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began on Friday with a great cocktail in honor of the 50th anniversary of the arrival of Jean Lesage at the head of the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes to rename the Beauharnois plant in Dam Adélard-Godbout.
"From Godbout, creator of Hydro-Québec, to Lesage which nationalized hydroelectricity, to Bourassa, creator of Bay James, our party has always been able to forge the future," said Jean Charest.
During the press conference, another conservative reference was made to the "Roads to the North" programme by John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
Addressing the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Charest pointed out that it would be put into operation in 2012.
"All this remains between us, but I feel that we will succeed," he confessed to his militants, arousing heartfelt applause.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said there would be no elections in April 2008 and probably not even in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of starting a poll in the autumn, which could happen in accordance with the law.
He stresses that he is certainly very committed, particularly on a mission of the Federal Council in China and in the Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend General Council provided the liberal leader with a platform of nationalist resolutions, in particular of the "constitutional aspirations" that have passed as smooth as oil: the PLQ calls above all for recognition of the "specificity of Quebec" in the Constitution.
It also hopes that Quebec will appoint the members of the Canadian Broadcasting and Telecommunications Council and that they will have a right of veto over the decisions taken in Quebec.
As far as the opposition is concerned, the draft of the North Plan has been sceptically accepted.
FP leader Pauline Marois dusted the Northern Development Policy of Quebec launched by the Landry government in 2001.
In your opinion, the liberal government, which came to power in 2003, would not have respected its application.
If he had done so," we would have progressed today," said Marois alongside Jean-Talon's candidate (scrutinium today), Françoise Mercure.
ADQ has stated its support for the adoption of the Northern Plan by the government.
"What we hope, is that all of this is not simply perceived as a spectacle," commented leader Sébastien Proulx, Mario Dumont's replacement, returning from the holidays today.
Letters - A Dishonored Country
It was Vic Toews, former minister of Justice (irony of fate) of Harper's cabinet, who dared to declare last summer that Louise Arbor was a "shame" for Canada.
To dishonor in this way a woman who has fought incessantly for justice and who deserves all our admiration says much about both the entourage of the Prime Minister and Stephen Harper himself.
We are faced with a government that is the only one, of all the Western countries involved, not to have returned one of its citizens detained in the Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that takes no account at all of the fact that Omar Khadr was a mere teenager at the time when the facts attributed to him occurred.
The only government that, despite signing the Geneva Convention, denies its word and lets a child-soldier rot in in inhumane conditions.
The only one who trusts in a parody of justice to establish the guilt of the accused.
We remind you, for information, that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, in particular, call for Omar Khadra's repatriation so that he can be brought to trial on a regular basis in Canada.
It is precisely that same government that closes its eyes to torture: it does not care very much that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, perhaps forever, after so many years of abuse.
We do not yet realize this, but we are witnessing an insidious erosion of our rights, freedom and "democracy", a word that Harper does not stop flaunting and which sounds so senseless on his lips.
Here we are at the moment when there is no longer any morale: you can abuse, torture, arbitrarily imprison a Canadian citizen according to the discretion of a minority head of government until today (see what will happen after October 14...).
Many voters believe that a party that preaches the Virtue, the Respect of the Law and the Order represent salvation: they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
This is where the shame lies, Mr. Toews, in giving up all this, and nowhere else.
Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In his September 17 edition, Le Devor published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice-president director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world's largest auriferous company has filed a six million libel lawsuit against three authors and a small, squatted publishing house with the intention of launching a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a complaint for defamation, but the law.
Without any surprise, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a substantial amount of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed from the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these fights with unequal weapons, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that gags the opposition in addition to frighten anyone who dares to pronounce on the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that it should have presented its own vision of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada usually take place with the exchange of views and not with batons.
It would have been sufficient for the company to open its books, its documents, and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and in a bad way rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is quite evident?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers exclusively to lawyers who are highly paid and not to the Canadians as a whole; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
