Operation - rescue for Wall Street – Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, representatives of the Republican and Democratic side, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the greatest bailout plan after the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has been weighing on Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by the two chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of foreclosures for non-payments, as well as a right of inspection on remuneration paid to managers of protected companies.
The American Secretary to the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an effective agreement on markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Every decision has been taken in such a way as to safeguard the economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It's the crucial point: if we hadn't acted like this, inestimable disappointments and upsets would have spilled over to the everyday lives of Americans," declared Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time limit agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
When they joined the negotiations later, the two US presidential candidates were quite in favour of the agreement, but did not avoid expressing their discontent with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama deserves credit for having added some provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow the owners to keep their homes and the one related to the wages for the managers of companies covered by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American TV screen.
Interviewed on another channel to see if he will vote in favour of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
"As far as I've read, it's something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward."
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the dubious, risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the outbreak of a real estate bubble that led first to the collapse of risk mortgage loans (borrowers) , and then extend to other more widespread forms of debt securities (PCAA) and lead to the freezing of liquidity and the collapse of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of reigning Republicans that blew up the first draft of a deal last week.
