The psychology of excessive bidding: why spend more money?
At auctions buyers are inclined to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study appeared in Science magazine men do not want to stay behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are also willing to pay a higher price.
Research has tried to trace the nervous pattern of this "game" at the level of the nervous system through experimental rods.
One group of volunteers played the lotto, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging method (fMRI) they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to licitate more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex enters intensively into operation when it loses to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-gratification" of the nervous system.
Thus, according to researchers, the price rise is explained by avoiding the vehement reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, research group economists conducted a financial pursuit investigation.
In this survey, three groups contested a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told what the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they have promised that in the case of winning they will receive another $15 prize.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost the money in case of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the win was underlined, while for the other the loss.
Compromising the neurologist hypothesis, the members of the group who played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "winner".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These, in fact, so far explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you contact your doctor?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver diseases are mentioned among the first causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread into two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal leakage, saliva).
For those traveling it is useful to immunize against virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots are formed on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the stools become clear and the urine dark, the healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die worldwide every year from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver tumors and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because the pathogens destroy the liver cells in a devious way, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more frequent than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
In the world to date, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease it is worth talking to the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University performed an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, said the British Telegraph.
In the context of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
On the basis of the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of researches in which, besides academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also take part.
The test was exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's ermine painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a tranquilizing effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time aro received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious theme painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe," as if "someone took care of them" and "have calmed down and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image, they accounted for 12% less pain than when Leonardo's work was before them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you have to find the right image.
"We need to look for an image to which they have very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the outcome of the research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality." - added Wright.
After the excellent results only the question remains if the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You're what you say about yourself
On the tenth birthday Google can claim to be in people's pockets as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which clinic they attend and what they care about.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's directors, this is not enough yet.
What concerns skeptics who compare with the Orwellian nightmare, they just don't see the substance of web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that Google's main purpose is to collect as much personal data as its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google's founders that it was: "let's put all the information in a system in the world!".
According to the Google director interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years Schmidt answered: he would like if Google could answer questions like "what do I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?", but software doesn't know how to answer seemingly simple questions because they don't know enough about users.
Not all internet users are aware that during their internet searches, exactly the words you search for are recorded, from which IP address they are searched for and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through Personalized Search launched two years ago users e.g. can store their browsing history, may relate what they have searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better customized results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services according to our preferences declared and recorded previously.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - concerned users are wondering about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, the counterreactions of the internet users are caused by the fear of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the guilt, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom or even the rebellion against power.
One fact is confirmed, however, that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases they can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times has perhaps been the coordinated action against Brazil's paedophiles, in which Google has forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that has made possible the identification of paedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users worried about personal rights instead sighed of relief in May when the company - in agreement with the Electronic Legal Protection Association EFF - successfully demonstrated the truth in court against the FBI: not even later can Google be forced with no point in the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government successfully ripped up nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to obtain the search lists of individual users and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back to two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data press Google because they believe that this undermines their intimate sphere and private life by beginning to use its services and rise up with the rebellion of the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile the American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users appeared in many countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, the Microsoft liquidated as conqueror of the world because of Windows, however both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code kept up to date and the package of programs is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies just one of the most frequently repeated keywords in recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 speaks of nothing but collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: show ourselves.
