The intelligent machine mimics the bumblebee’s flight
What could be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies than to imitate sensors of obstacles in nature?
Like bees.
In the amazing project presented to CEATIC in Japan the hornets gave the initial strategic inspiration to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotized miniauto with the properties of bees, with the final aim of creating a system able to avoid all collisions.
Flying the bees form their own personal oval space that looks very much like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a 300 degree view in every direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This avoiding maneuver, in a different way from the current system, takes place in an entirely instinctive way.
"If it weren't so, the robot car wouldn't be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damageable and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the steering direction of the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to avoid the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their duration is longer than those to lithium ions.
According to Andoh it is important the snapshot of the intelligent reaction, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot has to process some inputs in seconds and react.
There is no need to store and react with intuitive logic based on the previous manoeuvring data, so it only uses a memory of a few dozen Kb.
You don't need a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, provided for at Nissan, within 10 years can be installed on standard vehicles.
A further possibility of application may be the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system, which avoids obstacles on the road leading to its destination.
