Járóka, according to the press office of the parliamentary group Fidesz PE, recalled, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, that the Roma are expelled from the labour market in the first place because of their low schooling.
"Most Roma young people do not have the right to study at an average level, and as a result of poor basic education, only a small number of them can achieve a higher level of study."
Mr Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in upholding human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of EU member states.
According to the honourable Member, these links need to be made aware in the broader context of Roma and non-Roma.
In fact, the sooner the school starts a Roma, the more his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market grow; through taxes paid for income and consumption they contribute to the nation's budget.
"The Roma's right of European citizenship must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools" stressed Lívia Járóka.
According to the congresswoman, the union of purpose and action of the European Union is necessary in order to accelerate the processes of desegregation of schools, and for this reason it is of fundamental importance the proper respect of the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be interrupted, Roma children must be given the opportunities provided by the democratic area so that they can contribute as citizens to the full future of Europe," Járóka asked.
Under the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized every year, from last year's Berlin meeting is to ensure a unique forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at state and European level.
