Mp3 readers under charge, endangering hearing
Listening to high volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injury.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a statement issued in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion - it is stated in the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than one hour a day holding the high volume device risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high noise levels can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From scientific findings - continues the EU manager - a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical instruments and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - concludes the EU executive - confirm that there is a cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music equipment and related equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
Such damage can be greatly reduced by means of solutions such as reducing noise exposure levels and duration.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable musical equipment if they listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the limits currently in force for the maximum noise permitted at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5 to 10% of the users of these appliances and their number can be estimated at between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
