The figures provided by Anec, the main association of exhibitors, speak clearly: in the last five years have closed its doors 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay the biggest price are above all the halls in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but we should ensure the survival of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the non-allocation of the fund for exhibitors: the state's previous debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect existing laws.
In order to support the field they would serve between the 16 and 18 million euros the year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about closures, decided to take shelter with the signing of a protocol between Comune and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote cinemas single room both in the historical center and in the suburbs.
Among the proposed rules are tax facilitation measures in favour of operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special parking rates and some parking spaces.
"I like this initiative," Giuseppe Tornatore observes, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that in order to counteract the overpower of multiplexes traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Cinema Paradiso", which I have been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, not to see the black posters from the dust I turn to the other side".
Links between politics and 'ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to standardize the choices of the municipality to the interests of the Piromalli leg".
The accusations that the magistrates of the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria address to the mayor and the deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and to the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition in mafia association, are heavy.
In handcuffs also Gioacchino Piromalli, the elderly mediator between the clan and the public administrations, and his nephew lawyer, the boss's namesake, already sentenced for association for mafia-style delinquency, sentenced to compensate 10 million euros.
